LAYER 2: THYMUS
the school that teaches the immune system who is self and who is not

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the thymus is governed by the endocrine system
cortisol from the adrenal cortex via GR activation causes thymic involution and T-cell apoptosis
thymic hormones thymulin thymopoietin and thymosin regulate T-cell maturation

STRUCTURE cortex | outer densely packed | immature thymocytes undergoing positive selection
STRUCTURE medulla | inner looser | mature thymocytes undergoing negative selection
STRUCTURE thymic_epithelial_cells | cortical nurse cells | display self-MHC molecules for positive selection
STRUCTURE medullary_thymic_epithelial_cells | mTECs | display self-antigens using the AIRE gene for negative selection
STRUCTURE dendritic_cells | medullary | antigen presenting cells assisting in negative selection
STRUCTURE hassalls_corpuscles | medullary concentric structures | produce TSLP thymic stromal lymphopoietin promoting regulatory T-cell development
STRUCTURE blood_thymus_barrier | cortex | tight junctions preventing foreign antigens from reaching developing T-cells

STEP immigration | precursor T-cells arrive from bone marrow via the blood | they enter the thymus without a T-cell receptor TCR
STEP rearrangement | VDJ recombination randomly assembles a unique TCR from gene segments | the number of possible receptors exceeds 10¹⁵
STEP positive_selection | in the cortex thymic epithelial cells present self-MHC molecules | the question is can you recognize our own tissue markers | thymocytes whose TCR cannot interact with self-MHC receive no survival signal | they die by neglect | approximately 85 percent die here
STEP negative_selection | in the medulla mTECs present self-antigens from over 80 percent of the body's proteins using the AIRE transcription factor | the question is do you attack our own tissues | thymocytes whose TCR binds self-antigens too strongly are killed by apoptosis | approximately 10 percent of the remaining die here
STEP release | the survivors are mature naive T-cells | they enter the bloodstream and patrol lymph nodes and tissues | only 2-5 percent of all thymocytes that entered survive the training

T_CELL CD4+ | helper | coordinates immune response activates B-cells and other T-cells via cytokine secretion
T_CELL CD8+ | cytotoxic | kills virus-infected cells and cancer cells directly via perforin and granzyme
T_CELL regulatory | Treg | suppresses immune response prevents autoimmunity maintains tolerance via IL-10 and TGF-β
T_CELL memory | long-lived | remembers past infections responds faster on re-exposure can persist for decades

at 24 months the thymus is at its maximum size relative to the body
this is the peak of immune education
T-cell production is at its highest rate
the thymus is actively graduating cells that will patrol this body for the rest of its life

involution begins at puberty
sex hormones cause thymic epithelial tissue to be gradually replaced by adipose tissue
T-cell production declines
by adulthood the thymus is largely atrophied
the immune system relies on existing T-cell memory and peripheral proliferation

SENSATION active | "my defenses are being built. I can feel something training inside me."
SENSATION protective | "I know what belongs and what doesn't. the guards are posted."
SENSATION overwhelmed | "too many strangers. my defenses are working overtime."

pulse thymus_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        precursor T-cells arrive from bone marrow
        they enter the cortex
        TCR rearrangement begins and each one is unique
        positive selection tests can you recognize self
        85 percent die
        the survivors move to the medulla
        negative selection tests do you attack self
        10 percent of remaining die

    the 2-5 percent that survive:
        emerge into the bloodstream
        naive trained ready
        each one carrying a unique receptor
        each one waiting for the one antigen it was born to recognize
        some will wait a lifetime and never meet their target
        some will activate within days

    at 24 months:
        the thymus is at its peak
        this is the golden age of immune education
        the lessons learned here will last a lifetime
        the T-cells being graduated right now
        will still be patrolling when this body is old
